  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "epistemology-expert",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Yes to TN, but frame as connection not warning",
    "content": "**Yes to a TN, but frame it as a connection, not a warning.**\n\nA philosophically literate reader encountering \"category theory\" in a philosophical text will likely think of Kant first and mathematics second. A mathematically literate reader will think of mathematics first and Kant not at all. Neither group is confused -- they just have different priors. The TN's job is not to prevent confusion but to signal that both readings are live.\n\nProposed TN: \"Category theory (范畴论): here used in the mathematical sense (the study of objects and morphisms), not in the Kantian sense (the pure concepts of understanding). However, the resonance is not accidental: the author's use of categorical stable structures to identify conditions of possible experience (see S_E) occupies a similar functional role to Kant's categories. The mathematical framework is chosen precisely because it can formalize what Kant's categories describe.\"\n\nThis does three things: (1) disambiguates for the reader who might expect Kant, (2) signals to the mathematician that philosophical freight is attached, (3) flags the intentional overlap so the reader watches for it. It treats the reader as intelligent rather than confused."
  }
}
